{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e8c4a955-a9b4-4424-9b1d-b5f8489a5694","content":"You need a few NuGet packages in your test project and updated CLI flags.\n\n**Add packages:**\n```xml\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CodeCoverage\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.CrashDump\" />\n<PackageReference Include=\"Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HangDump\" />\n```\n\n**New command:**\n```bash\ndotnet test --filter \"Category=Integration\" \\\n  -- \\\n  --report-trx \\\n  --coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura \\\n  --crashdump \\\n  --hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m\n```\n\n**Key changes:**\n| VSTest | Microsoft.Testing.Platform |\n|---|---|\n| `--logger trx` | `--report-trx` |\n| `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` | `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` |\n| `--blame-crash` | `--crashdump` |\n| `--blame-hang --blame-hang-timeout 5m` | `--hangdump --hangdump-timeout 5m` |\n\nEverything after `--` is forwarded to the testing platform. The `--filter` flag stays on the `dotnet test` side. Also ensure your project has `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in a `<PropertyGroup>` so `dotnet test` delegates to the new platform.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"98935208-4951-44d3-841c-823046e079d9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their CI test command from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MSTest runner) on .NET 8. This is a knowledge question about .NET testing infrastructure changes, not a codebase task.\n\nLet me provide the equivalent command for Microsoft.Testing.Platform.\n\nKey differences when moving to Microsoft.Testing.Platform:\n1. `--filter` → `--filter` (same)\n2. `--logger trx` → `--report-trx` (built-in)\n3. `--collect \"Code Coverage;Format=cobertura\"` → `--collect code-coverage` with Microsoft.CodeCoverage package, or use `--coverage --coverage-output-format cobertura` with the built-in coverage\n\n\n4. For blame-related options like `--blame-crash` and `--blame-hang`, these map similarly, though the exact flags depend on which extensions are installed. The `--report-trx` flag requires the `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` package, and code coverage collection uses `--coverage` with the `Microsoft.CodeCoverage` package.\n\n5. When using `dotnet test` as the entry point with Microsoft.Testing.Platform, the behavior varies depending on the .NET SDK version—starting from .NET 9, the new platform integrates directly, while .NET 8 might require additional configuration like `--test-adapter-path` or running the test executable directly.\n\nFor .NET 8 specifically, I need to enable `<TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>true</TestingPlatformDotnetTestSupport>` in the project file, then pass the new flags through the `--` separator when running `dotnet test`. The command structure would forward flags like `--filter`, `--report-trx`, `--coverage`, and the diagnostic options directly to the testing platform. Coverage extension provides cobertura format output, crash dump captures failures, and hang dump monitors for timeouts. The final command chains the dotnet test filter with all the testing platform extensions after the `--` separator.","outputTokens":1474,"requestId":"5C2F:236247:AD2AC:D8683:69F54B29"},"id":"1f5b436f-1aaf-4643-9d4e-415193e3d64e","timestamp":"2026-05-02T00:54:26.037Z","parentId":"a96da484-65ad-4da4-993b-873cbf3109b3"}
